"The trees of the avenue stood motionless, like sentinels, their branches stretched towards us like withered arms.
The rhododendrons were not yet in bloom, but they loomed tall and dark, like silent witnesses to some ancient ritual.
I felt a shiver run down my spine as we turned in at the lodge gates and crunching gravel beneath our wheels was the only sound that broke the stillness.
The house rose before us, serene and untroubled, its many windows reflecting the sun's pale light.
The house, when it came into view, seemed larger and more imposing than I had imagined, its windows, unlit and staring, made it seem blind.
The drive curved about, the wood falling away on either side, and suddenly, as we rounded a bend, the house came into view.
The drive twisted and curved, the woods grew denser, the shadows deepened, and I could feel the presence of Manderley all around me, its grandeur and beauty, its melancholy and decay."
The long drive twisted and turned through the woods, the rhododendrons massed on either side, a tangled web of dark green leaves and crimson flowers.

The drive twisted and turned through the woods, now mounting a little, now dipping into a hollow, until suddenly it climbed to a summit and there before us lay the house, its windows like empty eyes staring back."
It was a place of enchantment, and a little eerie too...I wanted to get out and walk up the drive, to feel the grass beneath my feet, but Maxim did not stop the car until we came to the house itself.
And then I saw it, the grey stone, the pillared facade, the high roof and chimneys set against the sky."

And then, as he put on the brake, I saw it - Manderley..."
